<h3>Conference rationale:</h3>
<img src="http://www.physics.ox.ac.uk/confs/plasma_17/img/crab_web.jpg" alt="Workshop on Plasma Astrophysics from the Laboratory to the Non-Thermal Universe, 5-7 July, Oxford, UK" style="float: right; padding: 0px 10px 10px 30px;"/>
<p>
Recent years have seen rapid growth in the overlap between common areas of interest of laboratory plasma and high-energy astrophysicists. In particular, the physics being explored in current and future experiments using high power or high intensity lasers, address questions that are becoming increasingly relevant to understanding astrophysical phenomena. High-power facilities are already being used to study, for example,  the complex microphysical behaviour of  collisionless shocks or the turbulent amplification of magnetic fields; both topical issues in the study of astrophysical particle acceleration. As the next generation of lasers move into the ultra-high intensity regime, new opportunities to explore QED processes and high-field astrophysics will undoubtedly emerge. Numerical simulations of ever-increasing scale and sophistication march in parallel with this progress in experimental capability.
</p>
<p>
This workshop aims to exploit these, and other recent advances, bringing together experts in areas where there exists a clear potential for fruitful exchange of knowledge and discussion of outstanding issues, with an emphasis on areas of common interest.
</p>
<p>
We also take this opportunity to celebrate the distinguished careers of Professors Tony Bell and John Kirk, who have both made multiple invaluable contributions to these fields. 
</p>
